Type, proportion of cells varies with CT type, but in ordinary CT, the usual cast of characters is:
Fixed cells - primarily function locally:
fibroblasts: produce fibres, GS
fixed macrophages: avidly phagocytic
adipocytes: store lipids for energy, insulation, physical protection
mast cells: involved in mediating inflammation, hypersensitivity reactions 
mesenchymal cells: multipotential stem cells which, under different conditions, may differentiate into different cell types (fibrocytes, chondrocytes, osteocytes, adipocytes, smooth muscle cells)
Wandering cells -the numbers in CT spaces increase with tissue damage or infection:
monocytes:  drawn in by chemotactic signals, differentiate into macrophages
B-lymphocytes: become antibody-producing plasma cells with antigen exposure
microphages (neutrophils and eosinophils): circulate in blood, drawn into CT spaces by chemotactic signals released with tissue damage or infection
